-- Foreign Investors Buy Net 9.74 Billion Rupees of Indian Stocks
-- B y   P a r e s h   J a t a k i a
-- 2012-10-05T12:09:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-05/foreign-investors-buy-net-9-74-billion-rupees-of-indian-stocks.html
Overseas  investors  bought a net  9.74
billion rupees  of Indian stocks yesterday, raising their
investment in the equities this year to 857.1 billion rupees, or
$16.5 billion, according to the nation’s market regulator.  Foreigners bought 32.4 billion rupees of shares and sold
22.7 billion rupees, the Securities & Exchange Board of India
said on its  website  today. They bought 192.6 billion rupees of
stocks in September.  The benchmark  BSE India Sensitive Index (SENSEX)  has increased 22.5
percent this year, helped by the biggest overseas equity flows
among 10 Asian markets tracked by Bloomberg, excluding  China .
Flows surged to a record in 2010, making the Sensex the best
performer among the world’s top 10 markets. The largest-ever
outflow in 2008 led the biggest annual slump of 52 percent.  Overseas Funds bought a net 3.65 billion rupees of bonds,
taking total inflow into debt this year to 265.2 billion rupees,
the data  show .  Foreigners have invested 5.3 trillion rupees in stocks and
1.473 trillion rupees in bonds since they were allowed into the
country in 1993.  The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
